### \subsection{Diffusion and Flow Matching}
Diffusion models have achieved strong performance in generative modeling by learning to reverse a gradual noising process, enabling high-fidelity sample synthesis. Representative methods such as DDPM and score-based models parameterize denoising/score functions and generate samples via iterative sampling with SDE/ODE solvers, while works like DDIM improve efficiency by reducing sampling steps.  

To further alleviate the high inference cost of multi-step denoising, flow matching learns a continuous-time velocity field that transports samples from a simple prior to the data distribution. Sampling can then be performed by integrating an ODE, offering a more efficient and deterministic alternative that connects diffusion modeling with continuous normalizing flows.
